  "prompt": "What came before the multiverse?",
  "response": "The concept of the multiverse is a contemporary theoretical framework in cosmology and physics that posits the existence of multiple, possibly infinite, universes including our own. Before the advent of the multiverse theory, the prevailing idea was that of a single universe \u2014 the entirety of space, time, matter, and energy that we could observe and measure.\n\nPrior to the multiverse concept becoming a topic of scientific speculation and theoretical research, cosmological thinking was largely dominated by the Big Bang theory. The Big Bang theory posits that the universe originated from an extremely hot and dense state about 13.8 billion years ago and has been expanding ever since. This single-universe model was the main perspective in cosmology for much of the 20th century.\n\nBefore that, philosophical and religious interpretations offered various concepts of the universe's origins and nature, often involving creation myths or deities. In Western philosophy, ideas about the cosmos evolved from ancient Greek interpretations, such as the geocentric model of the universe proposed by Ptolemy, to the heliocentric model suggested by Copernicus, and later to Newtonian mechanics describing a predictable, clockwork universe.\n\nThe notion of the multiverse specifically arose from various lines of thought in modern theoretical physics, particularly in relation to string theory, quantum mechanics, and cosmic inflation. These theories sometimes imply the existence of many different universes or \"domains\" with varying physical properties.\n\nTo summarize, the concept of the multiverse builds on and extends beyond earlier single-universe theories, such as the Big Bang, and continues to address fundamental questions about the nature of existence and the cosmos.",
